1
00:00:05,678 --> 00:00:11,401
I'm supposed to tell you to turn off your cell phones and things like that, so please do that.

2
00:00:11,401 --> 00:00:16,024
And I'm supposed to also tell you to sort of like scoot in and make room for more people,

3
00:00:16,024 --> 00:00:18,085
but I see that's not really necessary, so good job.

4
00:00:18,085 --> 00:00:22,347
Okay, I really appreciate you guys all being here.

5
00:00:22,347 --> 00:00:24,869
This is actually my first time talking at GDC,

6
00:00:24,869 --> 00:00:31,232
so the fact that any of you are here at all really means something to me. Thanks.

7
00:00:33,528 --> 00:00:35,510
I'm guessing there are a lot of artists and designers in the room.

8
00:00:35,510 --> 00:00:37,891
That's kind of what I put on the schedule.

9
00:00:37,891 --> 00:00:38,752
So I hope you are.

10
00:00:38,752 --> 00:00:42,974
And if you're anything like the people I've worked with,

11
00:00:42,974 --> 00:00:44,215
or me for example,

12
00:00:44,215 --> 00:00:46,557
there are times when you're working on a project

13
00:00:46,557 --> 00:00:48,998
and it becomes difficult to sort of

14
00:00:48,998 --> 00:00:51,380
mesh a clear artistic vision

15
00:00:51,380 --> 00:00:53,641
with sort of a gameplay direction

16
00:00:53,641 --> 00:00:56,103
and combine them into something that works for everybody

17
00:00:56,103 --> 00:00:58,804
and makes sort of a harmonious whole for the game.

18
00:00:58,804 --> 00:01:01,606
And there can be a little bit of a clash between artists and designers.

19
00:01:02,347 --> 00:01:06,891
And one thing that we've done with our workflow to create the game Rayman Legends

20
00:01:06,891 --> 00:01:10,734
is build a tool and sort of a pipeline and a way of working

21
00:01:10,734 --> 00:01:16,339
that tries to sort of mitigate this issue a little bit and make the process smoother for everybody,

22
00:01:16,339 --> 00:01:18,941
but also make it really fast, intuitive, and flexible

23
00:01:18,941 --> 00:01:24,326
so that we can produce a lot and produce quality a lot faster than normal.

24
00:01:24,326 --> 00:01:27,950
So, who am I? Why am I here talking to you? Why do you care?

25
00:01:29,759 --> 00:01:33,162
I'm a game and level designer at Ubisoft Montpellier in southern France.

26
00:01:33,162 --> 00:01:36,546
I've had the pleasure of working with them for about three years now.

27
00:01:36,546 --> 00:01:40,770
I've been working exclusively on Rayman titles in the Ubiart framework, which is our tool

28
00:01:40,770 --> 00:01:42,231
that we use to build them.

29
00:01:42,231 --> 00:01:47,116
So I've got quite a bit of experience using this tool pretty much exclusively for my career.

30
00:01:47,116 --> 00:01:50,899
So I have a lot of experience that I'd like to share with you guys, and hopefully you'll

31
00:01:50,899 --> 00:01:52,340
take something interesting away from it.

32
00:01:52,340 --> 00:01:52,601
What's the plan?

33
00:01:56,385 --> 00:01:59,547
I'm going to start by just giving you a little bit of a rundown of our design process in a nutshell.

34
00:01:59,547 --> 00:02:03,469
So you can sort of see why it's an interesting process,

35
00:02:03,469 --> 00:02:10,574
or maybe why it's a little bit different from the ones that you're familiar with.

36
00:02:10,574 --> 00:02:13,636
Then of course, what's the tech?

37
00:02:13,636 --> 00:02:16,637
Why do we use this tool? What have we built to use?

38
00:02:16,637 --> 00:02:18,859
And how does it help us follow this process that we set for ourselves?

39
00:02:18,859 --> 00:02:22,341
And then of course I'm going to talk about Rayman.

40
00:02:22,341 --> 00:02:23,922
It's my only frame of reference.

41
00:02:25,476 --> 00:02:28,557
So I'm going to talk about some useful systems and tools that we have,

42
00:02:28,557 --> 00:02:30,937
case studies from the actual production of the game,

43
00:02:30,937 --> 00:02:35,378
and a little bit of a post-mortem to give you some insight into things that we know went right

44
00:02:35,378 --> 00:02:39,119
and things that we know could have gone a little bit better.

45
00:02:39,119 --> 00:02:40,279
And I'm going to end

46
00:02:40,279 --> 00:02:43,900
the presentation by giving you a little bit of information about

47
00:02:43,900 --> 00:02:47,861
a couple other games that are being made in the framework that aren't exactly Rayman.

48
00:02:47,861 --> 00:02:52,282
So I'm going to let you guys in on a little secret, okay?

49
00:02:53,062 --> 00:02:57,509
The secret to designing Rayman is actually quite similar to the secret of playing Rayman,

50
00:02:57,509 --> 00:03:01,695
which is rapid, iterative failure.

51
00:03:04,377 --> 00:03:06,898
So basically what I mean by that is

52
00:03:06,898 --> 00:03:08,859
with our tool, with our process,

53
00:03:08,859 --> 00:03:10,240
we can design so quickly,

54
00:03:10,240 --> 00:03:12,601
we can try a bunch of different things so fast,

55
00:03:12,601 --> 00:03:14,741
that we can fail so much more often.

56
00:03:14,741 --> 00:03:16,702
Sounds awesome, right?

57
00:03:16,702 --> 00:03:17,643
You fail about 40 times a day,

58
00:03:17,643 --> 00:03:20,104
but then you get one win before you go home for the night.

59
00:03:20,104 --> 00:03:20,924
And that's enough.

60
00:03:20,924 --> 00:03:23,645
Because tomorrow you have something to work from.

61
00:03:23,645 --> 00:03:26,506
And it's really great to be able to put all these ideas in front of somebody

62
00:03:26,506 --> 00:03:29,487
and prove concepts and disprove concepts

63
00:03:29,487 --> 00:03:30,568
really fast

64
00:03:30,568 --> 00:03:32,068
and know that you're moving in the right direction.

65
00:03:34,235 --> 00:03:38,758
So, one of these core philosophies we have to work from is no idea is sacred.

66
00:03:38,758 --> 00:03:43,660
I've seen a lot of people, I still see a lot of people do this, and I still do this myself

67
00:03:43,660 --> 00:03:46,102
sometimes that people hold on to an idea.

68
00:03:46,102 --> 00:03:48,163
It's like, no, no, no, but trust me, this is the best thing.

69
00:03:48,407 --> 00:03:50,148
We need this. It's gonna make or break the game.

70
00:03:50,148 --> 00:03:51,969
And they just put like little bandages.

71
00:03:51,969 --> 00:03:53,650
You know, it's like your arm just got cut off,

72
00:03:53,650 --> 00:03:55,010
but you're putting a band-aid on it.

73
00:03:55,010 --> 00:03:56,111
It's not really gonna change much.

74
00:03:56,111 --> 00:03:58,612
It's already messed up. It's not gonna happen.

75
00:03:58,612 --> 00:03:59,713
So why are you trying to fix it?

76
00:03:59,713 --> 00:04:01,714
And so sometimes it's just about learning

77
00:04:01,714 --> 00:04:03,655
when to let go of an idea

78
00:04:03,655 --> 00:04:05,395
and move on to something more promising.

79
00:04:05,395 --> 00:04:07,636
And that's usually what happens for us,

80
00:04:07,636 --> 00:04:10,458
is we're able to create so many different little ideas

81
00:04:10,458 --> 00:04:12,559
and different executions of the same idea

82
00:04:12,559 --> 00:04:14,720
that we learn to let go a lot quicker

83
00:04:14,720 --> 00:04:16,801
and move on in the right direction without too much fuss.

84
00:04:20,753 --> 00:04:26,097
I don't want to waste anybody's time, except for my own, because, I mean, I know why I'm

85
00:04:26,097 --> 00:04:26,618
wasting it.

86
00:04:26,618 --> 00:04:31,281
I have an idea, I want to see if it works, so I'm okay spending a bit of extra time to

87
00:04:31,281 --> 00:04:32,902
prove or disprove it.

88
00:04:32,902 --> 00:04:37,585
But I don't like the idea of briefing two programmers and an artist on an idea of mine,

89
00:04:37,585 --> 00:04:42,208
and then telling them, hey, invest two weeks of your time to make a prototype to prove

90
00:04:42,208 --> 00:04:44,069
or disprove whether or not this is a great idea.

91
00:04:44,069 --> 00:04:48,032
Because then after two weeks it sucks, and it's all my fault, and I wasted their time

92
00:04:48,032 --> 00:04:49,653
when they could have been doing something more important.

93
00:04:50,831 --> 00:04:57,401
So, I'm perfectly happy to spend a little bit of extra time doing a bit of art, doing a bit of scripting,

94
00:04:57,401 --> 00:05:03,130
and some sort of messy combination in our engine, to make something that works, or doesn't work,

95
00:05:03,130 --> 00:05:06,415
rather than actually having to go to someone that doesn't need to be involved yet.

96
00:05:06,475 --> 00:05:09,759
that allows the programmers and the artists to actually be investigating things

97
00:05:09,759 --> 00:05:11,842
that we know are going to be in the game later.

98
00:05:11,842 --> 00:05:16,227
Larger systems, things that are really important to investigate in the long term.

99
00:05:16,227 --> 00:05:19,371
And only when I've proven my concept to a creative director

100
00:05:19,371 --> 00:05:22,835
or somebody else that's important, do we actually invest the time to make it.

101
00:05:25,358 --> 00:05:30,200
We also tend to work together, but separately at the same time.

102
00:05:30,200 --> 00:05:34,361
What we basically do is, because you know when you're making a level, right?

103
00:05:34,361 --> 00:05:39,423
You build the level design layer, and then it's time for the artist to start doing his art pass.

104
00:05:39,423 --> 00:05:42,103
And it's like, okay, give me the level, it's my turn to work on it.

105
00:05:42,103 --> 00:05:43,204
Okay, fine.

106
00:05:43,204 --> 00:05:45,904
But then you're kind of got some downtime, and every time you want to work on it,

107
00:05:45,904 --> 00:05:48,205
you have to sort of like pass it back and forth,

108
00:05:48,205 --> 00:05:50,606
unless you're working in a more structured way.

109
00:05:50,606 --> 00:05:52,626
I mean, at least that's how I've done it in the past, which is a shame.

110
00:05:53,427 --> 00:05:55,531
So what we do is we basically say,

111
00:05:55,531 --> 00:05:57,596
this is the level design layer, right?

112
00:05:57,596 --> 00:05:58,999
This is where I'm building my level,

113
00:05:58,999 --> 00:06:01,444
all the gameplay elements in the game plane.

114
00:06:02,584 --> 00:06:05,306
no bullshit, just the stuff that I need, right?

115
00:06:05,306 --> 00:06:06,347
Then there's the art layer.

116
00:06:06,347 --> 00:06:08,068
It's in the exact same level,

117
00:06:08,068 --> 00:06:10,791
but it's only the art elements that complement

118
00:06:10,791 --> 00:06:13,013
the visual aspect of what I've created.

119
00:06:13,013 --> 00:06:16,115
And that's inside of the root file, of course.

120
00:06:16,115 --> 00:06:18,297
So you have one scene, which is the entire level.

121
00:06:18,297 --> 00:06:20,079
And then you have sub-scenes

122
00:06:20,079 --> 00:06:23,582
that are manipulable individually by different people.

123
00:06:23,582 --> 00:06:26,384
And when they send their updates,

124
00:06:26,384 --> 00:06:28,566
and I can get the new data and open it,

125
00:06:28,927 --> 00:06:32,869
When I open the whole file, their part is updated, and I'm still working on my thing.

126
00:06:32,869 --> 00:06:34,650
So nobody is slowed down in the process.

127
00:06:34,650 --> 00:06:36,591
And that's extremely important.

128
00:06:36,591 --> 00:06:39,873
Because that means that once I stumble upon that little gem,

129
00:06:39,873 --> 00:06:42,034
where it's like, ah, this is the idea that's working,

130
00:06:42,034 --> 00:06:44,916
let's move on from there, and everybody approves it,

131
00:06:44,916 --> 00:06:46,857
the artist can start working on that already,

132
00:06:46,857 --> 00:06:50,780
while I'm continuing to flesh it out and work on new things.

133
00:06:50,780 --> 00:06:52,601
And also we need to remain flexible,

134
00:06:52,601 --> 00:06:54,042
because later when you're debugging,

135
00:06:54,042 --> 00:06:57,244
or when you're sort of re-evaluating work you've already done a while ago,

136
00:06:58,065 --> 00:07:01,227
You want to reserve the right to be able to adjust things

137
00:07:01,227 --> 00:07:04,388
without having to adjust all the artwork too.

138
00:07:04,388 --> 00:07:10,130
On Rayman, it's especially important for us to design with the artist in mind.

139
00:07:10,130 --> 00:07:12,591
We can't just make something that we think plays cool,

140
00:07:12,591 --> 00:07:13,792
oh, it looks a lot of fun, whatever.

141
00:07:13,792 --> 00:07:16,413
No, but trust me, the inputs are great,

142
00:07:16,413 --> 00:07:18,074
and I'm teaching the player exactly what I need to,

143
00:07:18,074 --> 00:07:19,114
so it's going to be great.

144
00:07:19,114 --> 00:07:21,395
And then the artist has to go in there and say,

145
00:07:21,395 --> 00:07:23,056
oh, but how am I supposed to decorate this?

146
00:07:23,056 --> 00:07:25,357
It just doesn't work, it looks like crap, what are you doing?

147
00:07:25,357 --> 00:07:27,578
It's like, yeah, but trust me, it's important for the game.

148
00:07:27,758 --> 00:07:30,180
It's like they're not your mom, they don't just come in and clean up your mess

149
00:07:30,180 --> 00:07:34,863
because you're the designer and you're all powerful and you say what you want and it has to go.

150
00:07:34,863 --> 00:07:38,065
And so we try to design with the artist in mind.

151
00:07:38,065 --> 00:07:39,566
What they do is they create art kits.

152
00:07:39,566 --> 00:07:43,068
I mean, when you've got art this beautiful, do you really want to mess it up?

153
00:07:43,068 --> 00:07:47,772
Or do you want to complement it and make the whole game feel better?

154
00:07:47,772 --> 00:07:50,213
So they give us an art kit, something like this for example.

155
00:07:50,213 --> 00:07:54,536
This is a concept, but they can actually extract the artwork from it and make a kit out of it.

156
00:07:55,217 --> 00:08:00,079
So in this case, it's a nice, you know, flat ground, some little hills with flowers on it,

157
00:08:00,079 --> 00:08:03,981
and you say, oh, I want to make a right angle, because I want to have a wall jump.

158
00:08:03,981 --> 00:08:07,123
It just doesn't work. It looks ugly. It doesn't make any sense.

159
00:08:07,123 --> 00:08:10,865
And so what we have to do is think, do we need this wall jump?

160
00:08:10,865 --> 00:08:13,566
Or can I think of an interesting alternative,

161
00:08:13,566 --> 00:08:17,668
or a totally different idea altogether that complements the kit that I've been given?

162
00:08:17,969 --> 00:08:23,336
And that's one of the cores of the production on the design side of Rayman Legends and Rayman Origins

163
00:08:23,336 --> 00:08:27,682
is that we're constantly thinking about the rules and the constraints that the artists have given us

164
00:08:27,682 --> 00:08:31,247
with the artwork they've created, and trying to use it to our advantage

165
00:08:31,247 --> 00:08:33,671
rather than seeing it as something that's holding us back.

166
00:08:36,147 --> 00:08:39,208
This is an example of when I was doing pre-production for one of the worlds in the game.

167
00:08:39,208 --> 00:08:42,069
It was supposed to be an underwater base.

168
00:08:42,069 --> 00:08:45,391
And I didn't really know what the topology should be like.

169
00:08:45,391 --> 00:08:47,952
And there wasn't any concept, which was rare for us.

170
00:08:47,952 --> 00:08:51,333
Normally the artists do concepts and we build on top of those.

171
00:08:51,333 --> 00:08:52,754
But here we didn't have the time.

172
00:08:52,754 --> 00:08:56,335
And I had to investigate before they could actually draw something.

173
00:08:56,335 --> 00:08:59,976
So I was thinking about what could I do to make interesting topology

174
00:08:59,976 --> 00:09:04,698
that would fit with the setting that I already knew.

175
00:09:06,079 --> 00:09:12,062
But it had to be solid and artistic and so you can see that for example the larger pipes are sort of the borders and

176
00:09:12,062 --> 00:09:18,206
The smaller pipes are connected things don't feel unbalanced it all sort of it's a solid and on top of that

177
00:09:18,206 --> 00:09:22,729
I had an interesting gameplay layer. You know it's actually a fun level to play

178
00:09:22,729 --> 00:09:26,091
So then I passed that to the concept artist and he paints over it

179
00:09:26,452 --> 00:09:28,713
And then of course, it looks good.

180
00:09:28,713 --> 00:09:30,314
I mean, it's a rough concept, but it says,

181
00:09:30,314 --> 00:09:33,096
hey, that layout actually works. Not bad.

182
00:09:33,096 --> 00:09:36,318
So then we go through the process of approving things,

183
00:09:36,318 --> 00:09:37,598
and one thing leads to another.

184
00:09:37,598 --> 00:09:39,580
The artists make the final assets.

185
00:09:39,580 --> 00:09:41,021
We integrate it into the level.

186
00:09:41,021 --> 00:09:43,102
The level design didn't change.

187
00:09:43,102 --> 00:09:44,163
I defined the topology.

188
00:09:44,163 --> 00:09:47,465
And at the same time, the artist had what they needed

189
00:09:47,465 --> 00:09:49,406
to be able to make something beautiful.

190
00:09:49,406 --> 00:09:52,548
But it's because I designed with the artist in mind from the beginning.

191
00:09:55,624 --> 00:09:57,745
So how is this magical process done?

192
00:09:57,745 --> 00:10:01,246
It's not necessarily the easiest thing in the world to say we make

193
00:10:01,246 --> 00:10:02,926
five million prototypes every week,

194
00:10:02,926 --> 00:10:06,047
throw away four million of them, we have one little gem and everyone's happy.

195
00:10:06,047 --> 00:10:07,608
Not everybody has that luxury.

196
00:10:07,608 --> 00:10:10,609
Of course we have a very talented team.

197
00:10:10,609 --> 00:10:12,089
That's important. We work well together.

198
00:10:12,089 --> 00:10:17,091
But also we have an interesting piece of technology that we developed

199
00:10:17,091 --> 00:10:20,352
for Rayman Origins and have been constantly updating alongside the

200
00:10:20,352 --> 00:10:21,732
development of future titles.

201
00:10:24,069 --> 00:10:27,192
So the magic tech is the Ubiart framework.

202
00:10:27,192 --> 00:10:31,236
I'm going to show you a little video just to get you into the mood,

203
00:10:31,236 --> 00:10:34,599
and then we'll continue from there, and I'll give you some more details

204
00:10:34,599 --> 00:10:37,321
on why it's an interesting tool for me as a designer.

205
00:12:16,794 --> 00:12:22,898
kind of pretty right? Not bad. So as it said, the tool was designed for artists.

206
00:12:22,898 --> 00:12:28,981
So it's, it's a, it was a 2D game engine. It always was. It's what it was designed for.

207
00:12:28,981 --> 00:12:33,183
It has full HD, 60 frames per second, all that technical nonsense. But it's impressive.

208
00:12:33,183 --> 00:12:37,186
I mean, our games are very fast and fluid. We can have a lot of detailed textures in

209
00:12:37,186 --> 00:12:40,968
there. We have a lot of layers. And it still runs very, very smoothly. And that was one

210
00:12:40,968 --> 00:12:44,950
of the key selling points for us when building this tech. It needed to run well.

211
00:12:46,882 --> 00:12:49,608
but it's artist-friendly at its core.

212
00:12:49,608 --> 00:12:54,357
I mean, what an artist has to do to get an asset from concept

213
00:12:54,357 --> 00:12:58,044
into the engine in the playable game, all he has to do

214
00:12:58,044 --> 00:12:58,605
is paint a concept.

215
00:12:59,328 --> 00:13:04,011
cut a piece out, like a tree or a rock or something that he likes in the scenery,

216
00:13:04,011 --> 00:13:06,712
save it out with an alpha channel, drag and drop and it's in the engine.

217
00:13:06,712 --> 00:13:12,775
And they can just scale, move it around, whatever, change the colors, change the distance in the Z, everything like that.

218
00:13:12,775 --> 00:13:13,355
But it's that easy.

219
00:13:13,355 --> 00:13:19,378
There are other, more complicated methods of bringing art into the engine that I'm going to show you,

220
00:13:19,378 --> 00:13:20,739
that help me as a designer.

221
00:13:21,419 --> 00:13:28,611
But it doesn't change the fact that it's extremely easy for artists and designers to create content in this engine

222
00:13:28,611 --> 00:13:32,037
because it was built with the artist in mind.

223
00:13:32,037 --> 00:13:36,043
And it's fast, intuitive, and flexible in everything that it does.

224
00:13:40,743 --> 00:13:43,806
So, just a little bit of information on the Rayman series,

225
00:13:43,806 --> 00:13:46,950
because that's where all the examples are going to be coming from.

226
00:13:46,950 --> 00:13:50,674
Like I said, I got the chance to work on Origins and Legends.

227
00:13:50,674 --> 00:13:53,277
And back in 2011, when we released Origins,

228
00:13:53,277 --> 00:13:55,159
we had four-player co-op,

229
00:13:55,159 --> 00:13:59,804
a large number of levels, HD 2D graphics, 60 frames per second, all that stuff I said, right?

230
00:14:00,665 --> 00:14:03,947
And of course when you're making a sequel, you don't want to just make a direct sequel.

231
00:14:03,947 --> 00:14:07,570
You want to actually make it meaningful, make it something that people want to buy.

232
00:14:07,570 --> 00:14:11,272
So we wanted to add new features, make the engine more robust.

233
00:14:11,272 --> 00:14:14,395
This is just a small list. We have a lot of new additions that we made

234
00:14:14,395 --> 00:14:17,297
during the course of transitioning from Origins to Legends.

235
00:14:17,297 --> 00:14:21,059
But some big changes we made were online functionality that we didn't have before.

236
00:14:21,847 --> 00:14:25,790
a lighting system, touchscreen gameplay, 3D bosses.

237
00:14:25,790 --> 00:14:29,532
We didn't have support for any 3D objects in the environment before, and then we added

238
00:14:29,532 --> 00:14:32,654
it for Rayman Legends, and the game still runs the same.

239
00:14:32,654 --> 00:14:37,897
So we wanted to make sure that we're constantly updating our technology to give us the capability

240
00:14:37,897 --> 00:14:41,419
to do more than we ever thought that we could with the tool.

241
00:14:41,419 --> 00:14:46,642
And it also gives us a larger range of things that we can actually do to surprise the player.

242
00:14:49,857 --> 00:14:53,459
So this is sort of like the most impressive part of the talk.

243
00:14:53,459 --> 00:14:57,181
I'm going to be showing quite a few videos of the tools that we use

244
00:14:57,181 --> 00:15:00,283
and explaining sort of why they're interesting from the perspective of a designer.

245
00:15:00,283 --> 00:15:02,684
I think they're kind of going to speak for themselves,

246
00:15:02,684 --> 00:15:06,447
but I'll talk anyway because I like to do it.

247
00:15:06,447 --> 00:15:08,208
So here's the biggest one.

248
00:15:08,208 --> 00:15:09,508
It's our gameplay geometry.

249
00:15:09,508 --> 00:15:11,350
And for some reason it's called freezes.

250
00:15:11,350 --> 00:15:12,790
I think it's a French thing, but I don't really know.

251
00:15:12,790 --> 00:15:18,214
And basically, you just double-click and you start dragging vertices around.

252
00:15:18,785 --> 00:15:22,045
It's like manipulating something in a 3D modeling package on a plane,

253
00:15:22,045 --> 00:15:25,726
but what's impressive is that it's graphically complete.

254
00:15:25,726 --> 00:15:27,407
All the textures are already there.

255
00:15:27,407 --> 00:15:30,228
As you move the vertices around,

256
00:15:30,228 --> 00:15:32,668
the textures update depending on the angle

257
00:15:32,668 --> 00:15:35,489
that the vertex is at, for example.

258
00:15:35,489 --> 00:15:38,890
So when you have a vertical face, it changes to a cliffside.

259
00:15:38,890 --> 00:15:41,230
If it's horizontal, then you're going to get the grass.

260
00:15:42,190 --> 00:15:46,155
And of course I can check and see where Rayman's been for the past few steps,

261
00:15:46,155 --> 00:15:52,282
which allows me to quickly add new elements and improve my level or continue designing the level I'm working on.

262
00:15:52,282 --> 00:15:56,947
So that thing was a little bit too high, now I brought it down and it feels better.

263
00:15:56,947 --> 00:15:59,870
And I can move on to the next step, so I can bring a platform in.

264
00:16:00,965 --> 00:16:08,288
And just this ease of use is really the key to making so many prototypes all day, every day,

265
00:16:08,288 --> 00:16:09,929
and being okay with throwing them away.

266
00:16:09,929 --> 00:16:14,051
Because if it takes you five minutes to make an entire screen sequence,

267
00:16:14,051 --> 00:16:15,512
who cares if you have to throw it away?

268
00:16:15,512 --> 00:16:17,213
That's business as usual.

269
00:16:17,213 --> 00:16:19,054
But if you had to draw it out on paper,

270
00:16:19,054 --> 00:16:21,935
and then convince somebody to help you build something so you can do your sequence,

271
00:16:21,935 --> 00:16:23,836
and then it takes you three weeks, and then, oh, it doesn't work?

272
00:16:25,450 --> 00:16:27,492
you're not going to be happy throwing that away exactly.

273
00:16:27,492 --> 00:16:30,153
I can actually pause while I'm playing too.

274
00:16:30,153 --> 00:16:32,795
And I can place things where they need to be.

275
00:16:32,795 --> 00:16:35,496
So I can sort of have real great precision

276
00:16:35,496 --> 00:16:37,677
on where my enemies are going to be placed, where my platforms are.

277
00:16:37,677 --> 00:16:39,198
And then I just press P and I'm back to the game.

278
00:16:39,198 --> 00:16:42,340
So the most important thing about all of this

279
00:16:42,340 --> 00:16:44,201
is that the game is live

280
00:16:44,201 --> 00:16:46,743
while you're manipulating anything in the environment.

281
00:16:46,743 --> 00:16:50,825
It's really, really important for the speed of iteration,

282
00:16:50,825 --> 00:16:52,066
for testing your sequences,

283
00:16:52,066 --> 00:16:54,067
for knowing that what you're doing is actually working or not.

284
00:16:55,184 --> 00:16:58,425
and everything that we have in this tool just helps to

285
00:16:58,425 --> 00:17:01,366
push that feeling of flexibility, creativity,

286
00:17:01,366 --> 00:17:05,347
and allowing someone to express themselves with minimal hassle.

287
00:17:05,347 --> 00:17:08,028
And also what's interesting about this visually complete geometry

288
00:17:08,028 --> 00:17:10,868
is that just in the level design layer,

289
00:17:10,868 --> 00:17:13,649
you already have a visually representative prototype

290
00:17:13,649 --> 00:17:15,950
of what the final thing might look like.

291
00:17:15,950 --> 00:17:18,430
You know that it's cliffs and grass,

292
00:17:18,430 --> 00:17:20,731
and you know when something doesn't look right.

293
00:17:20,791 --> 00:17:22,792
It's easy for us to fall into the trap of just saying,

294
00:17:22,792 --> 00:17:24,473
I'm going to use white box,

295
00:17:24,473 --> 00:17:27,474
make something that I think could look like a space station,

296
00:17:27,474 --> 00:17:28,755
and then the artist looks at it and says,

297
00:17:28,755 --> 00:17:31,016
how am I supposed to make a space station out of this?

298
00:17:31,016 --> 00:17:32,037
This doesn't make any sense.

299
00:17:32,037 --> 00:17:34,298
It's too organic, it's too this, it's too that.

300
00:17:34,298 --> 00:17:35,458
And what this does is they say,

301
00:17:35,458 --> 00:17:37,780
these are the things that you can use,

302
00:17:37,780 --> 00:17:39,040
this is how they work,

303
00:17:39,040 --> 00:17:40,901
work within those constraints.

304
00:17:40,901 --> 00:17:43,302
And it changes the way that we have to think about our levels,

305
00:17:43,302 --> 00:17:43,983
for the better.

306
00:17:46,490 --> 00:17:48,692
So, we have other types of freezes though.

307
00:17:48,692 --> 00:17:51,294
We have pipe freezes, which are simpler to manipulate

308
00:17:51,294 --> 00:17:53,815
because you only need about two or three vertices

309
00:17:53,815 --> 00:17:55,777
and everything is already built around it.

310
00:17:55,777 --> 00:17:58,959
The collision, the shape, the way that everything looks.

311
00:17:58,959 --> 00:18:02,101
So it's extremely fast to just build a pipe network,

312
00:18:02,101 --> 00:18:03,161
connect things to one another.

313
00:18:03,161 --> 00:18:05,743
What you're seeing here actually,

314
00:18:05,743 --> 00:18:07,804
since we don't have perspective in the game,

315
00:18:07,804 --> 00:18:09,245
we obviously have to fake it somehow

316
00:18:09,245 --> 00:18:10,666
to make the game look nice.

317
00:18:11,600 --> 00:18:14,583
So we have the ability to add two extremity textures

318
00:18:14,583 --> 00:18:17,445
on the same area, basically, of the freeze,

319
00:18:17,445 --> 00:18:20,008
and we can switch between the two at any time.

320
00:18:20,008 --> 00:18:23,491
So we just say, OK, Rayman needs to stand on top of this,

321
00:18:23,491 --> 00:18:25,673
and perspective-wise, this looks wrong.

322
00:18:25,673 --> 00:18:27,795
So you just right-click, switch texture,

323
00:18:27,795 --> 00:18:32,178
and then it looks the way it's supposed to.

324
00:18:32,178 --> 00:18:32,959
It's super fast.

325
00:18:36,593 --> 00:18:38,556
We also have this thing called Metaphreezes.

326
00:18:38,556 --> 00:18:40,879
This is something that we actually designed

327
00:18:40,879 --> 00:18:43,081
during the production of Rayman Legends,

328
00:18:43,081 --> 00:18:44,663
so it was an addition later,

329
00:18:44,663 --> 00:18:47,146
because we realized, yeah, everything's live,

330
00:18:47,146 --> 00:18:47,967
even the enemy's dying.

331
00:18:49,672 --> 00:18:53,214
we realized that we were sort of working backwards sometimes.

332
00:18:53,214 --> 00:18:57,678
We were actually having three or four freezes we had to manipulate at the same time every time.

333
00:18:57,678 --> 00:19:00,360
And that's not really something you want to do.

334
00:19:00,360 --> 00:19:02,742
So what we did is we combined multiple freezes,

335
00:19:02,742 --> 00:19:06,185
the background, the playground, the foreground of this platform,

336
00:19:06,185 --> 00:19:07,646
into one manipulable object.

337
00:19:08,167 --> 00:19:10,609
What that does is it preserves the flexibility of the tiling

338
00:19:10,609 --> 00:19:12,050
of each of the individual freezes

339
00:19:12,050 --> 00:19:14,372
without causing unnecessary stretching or compromising

340
00:19:14,372 --> 00:19:15,773
the visual quality, and at the same time,

341
00:19:15,773 --> 00:19:17,575
preserving the flexibility of manipulation, which

342
00:19:17,575 --> 00:19:18,335
is extremely important for us.

343
00:19:18,335 --> 00:19:19,076
These ones are really cool.

344
00:19:19,076 --> 00:19:21,078
They look a bit like pipe freezes,

345
00:19:21,078 --> 00:19:22,719
but they're nothing like pipe freezes.

346
00:19:35,032 --> 00:19:37,813
They're Bezier, so they're spline controlled.

347
00:19:37,813 --> 00:19:39,713
And the collision is dynamically generated

348
00:19:39,713 --> 00:19:41,534
based on the spline that you have.

349
00:19:41,534 --> 00:19:43,434
It's updated in real time, obviously,

350
00:19:43,434 --> 00:19:45,035
and manipulation is extremely easy.

351
00:19:45,035 --> 00:19:48,096
You can see it's also visually complete,

352
00:19:48,096 --> 00:19:49,817
like all the other freezes.

353
00:19:49,817 --> 00:19:52,378
It tiles properly, stretches, updates.

354
00:19:52,378 --> 00:19:55,278
You're playing it, it's live, just like everything else.

355
00:19:55,278 --> 00:19:57,099
And there are a lot of extra parameters

356
00:19:57,099 --> 00:19:58,079
on top of these things

357
00:19:58,079 --> 00:20:00,260
that make them even more interesting for prototyping.

358
00:20:01,163 --> 00:20:06,427
One thing you can also see here is that we use the same system of manipulation for our collectibles now.

359
00:20:06,427 --> 00:20:11,850
In Rayman Origins, we actually placed every single loom, the little collectible guys,

360
00:20:11,850 --> 00:20:13,991
we used to place every single one by hand.

361
00:20:13,991 --> 00:20:19,935
And now all we have to do is put a spline to say they start here, they end there, you trigger it,

362
00:20:19,935 --> 00:20:21,956
and they just sort of fly to the end position.

363
00:20:23,799 --> 00:20:30,281
So it just makes the whole level design process that little bit less tedious

364
00:20:30,281 --> 00:20:35,063
and that makes it fine if I throw it away.

365
00:20:35,063 --> 00:20:37,864
It didn't take me 10 minutes just to place 500 stupid looms.

366
00:20:37,864 --> 00:20:39,044
It took me two seconds, so I can delete them.

367
00:20:39,044 --> 00:20:39,304
Who cares?

368
00:20:39,304 --> 00:20:44,306
We also have things like the ability to make them grow and retract,

369
00:20:44,306 --> 00:20:45,306
just with a simple trigger.

370
00:20:46,172 --> 00:20:50,235
And now, of course, if you're a designer, you can imagine all kinds of interesting things you can do with this.

371
00:20:50,235 --> 00:20:50,935
And that's not all.

372
00:20:50,935 --> 00:20:54,197
But it's just one of the many little features that were added

373
00:20:54,197 --> 00:20:57,559
that just brings so much more to the table as a designer to make creative levels.

374
00:20:57,559 --> 00:21:00,481
And when it's integrated into a visually complete package,

375
00:21:00,481 --> 00:21:01,642
there's no reason not to use it.

376
00:21:01,642 --> 00:21:04,804
So here's just a little example of a combination of some traditional freezes,

377
00:21:04,804 --> 00:21:05,464
some Bezier freezes, some animation.

378
00:21:15,472 --> 00:21:16,712
and a coin.

379
00:21:16,712 --> 00:21:17,293
And that's about it.

380
00:21:17,293 --> 00:21:20,855
It's just a combination of a couple simple systems.

381
00:21:20,855 --> 00:21:24,858
To build this, it wouldn't take more than five minutes for us.

382
00:21:24,858 --> 00:21:26,719
It's really, really fast.

383
00:21:26,719 --> 00:21:28,480
And I'm talking about visually speaking, too.

384
00:21:28,480 --> 00:21:29,881
The background, foreground, who cares?

385
00:21:29,881 --> 00:21:31,983
But the stuff that you're playing on,

386
00:21:31,983 --> 00:21:33,764
it looks like that when you build it.

387
00:21:33,764 --> 00:21:34,864
There's no extra work necessary.

388
00:21:37,857 --> 00:21:40,640
Of course, every level designer needs white box

389
00:21:40,640 --> 00:21:45,183
because there are some prototypes that you just need the freedom to do what you want

390
00:21:45,183 --> 00:21:46,544
exactly the way that you want.

391
00:21:46,544 --> 00:21:50,267
It's cool to have these visually complete freezes, but sometimes we don't know where

392
00:21:50,267 --> 00:21:51,248
we're going with the world

393
00:21:51,248 --> 00:21:55,372
or where the specific sequence fits into the grand scheme of the game.

394
00:21:55,372 --> 00:21:57,814
As you can see, it's still flexible, like everything else.

395
00:21:57,814 --> 00:22:00,075
It's very fast to work with this kind of stuff.

396
00:22:00,075 --> 00:22:04,119
But what's really powerful for me personally about these white box freezes

397
00:22:04,119 --> 00:22:06,261
is what I can do with them when it comes to prototyping.

398
00:22:07,304 --> 00:22:09,787
Because I can combine them with other elements

399
00:22:09,787 --> 00:22:11,509
and I can make my own gameplay.

400
00:22:11,509 --> 00:22:15,594
Basically, it's just a mixture of a couple different freezes,

401
00:22:15,594 --> 00:22:18,458
a couple movement tweens, and a trigger.

402
00:22:18,458 --> 00:22:21,181
And what I've basically simulated is

403
00:22:21,181 --> 00:22:23,864
a button that gets pressed and it triggers a door to open.

404
00:22:24,938 --> 00:22:28,459
And that's just the speed at which I can make a gameplay element

405
00:22:28,459 --> 00:22:32,640
that would normally take an artist and some programmers some time to develop

406
00:22:32,640 --> 00:22:33,800
before it can prove that it works.

407
00:22:33,800 --> 00:22:36,441
I've proven that it worked in about half a day of work.

408
00:22:36,441 --> 00:22:40,001
And I can easily manipulate it too, if the scale is wrong,

409
00:22:40,001 --> 00:22:41,461
if the shape is a bit wrong, or the color.

410
00:22:41,461 --> 00:22:42,282
One thing I like to do too, is white box sketching.

411
00:22:42,282 --> 00:22:42,462
I'm sorry.

412
00:22:57,572 --> 00:22:58,652
I don't know what happened.

413
00:22:58,652 --> 00:23:02,315
I'm going to continue while this boots up.

414
00:23:02,315 --> 00:23:04,077
I'm really, really sorry.

415
00:23:04,077 --> 00:23:04,597
I don't know why.

416
00:23:04,597 --> 00:23:10,502
One thing I like to do is I really take this sort of white box geometry and I sketch what

417
00:23:10,502 --> 00:23:11,783
it is that I want it to look like.

418
00:23:11,783 --> 00:23:18,909
Because what I need to do is I have to convince the artist and everybody of what my vision

419
00:23:18,909 --> 00:23:19,309
is, basically.

420
00:23:19,309 --> 00:23:24,073
What I could do is I could simply make this object a red circle and say it's a dangerous

421
00:23:24,073 --> 00:23:24,453
object.

422
00:23:24,453 --> 00:23:24,614
Go.

423
00:23:25,425 --> 00:23:29,627
And the artist, okay, well, what do you want for this red circle and all that kind of stuff?

424
00:23:29,627 --> 00:23:31,168
And they have to figure it out.

425
00:23:31,168 --> 00:23:33,470
But for me, I think it's important that it has spikes.

426
00:23:33,470 --> 00:23:36,272
It needs to be clear why it's dangerous for the player.

427
00:23:36,272 --> 00:23:39,294
Because science and feedback are important, right?

428
00:23:39,294 --> 00:23:41,695
And so the ability for me to actually sketch that out

429
00:23:41,695 --> 00:23:45,938
makes it a lot more powerful for me to be able to pitch that idea to somebody.

430
00:23:46,539 --> 00:23:51,385
And what's interesting is when you look at the final art asset, basically,

431
00:23:51,385 --> 00:23:56,251
it looks relatively similar to what I was able to actually produce with the white box.

432
00:23:56,251 --> 00:23:57,092
So it makes sense.

433
00:23:59,553 --> 00:24:02,115
And actually this is one of the things that I do on a daily basis.

434
00:24:02,115 --> 00:24:06,038
It's one of the things that is the strongest thing for me

435
00:24:06,038 --> 00:24:07,880
as a level designer in this engine

436
00:24:07,880 --> 00:24:10,602
is to be able to sketch things out like this so rapidly.

437
00:24:10,602 --> 00:24:13,244
What you could say is, you can just draw it out in Photoshop

438
00:24:13,244 --> 00:24:15,165
and drag and drop it into the engine.

439
00:24:15,165 --> 00:24:16,766
Okay, why not? That's fine.

440
00:24:16,766 --> 00:24:18,387
That's what it's built for, right?

441
00:24:18,387 --> 00:24:19,808
But for someone like me,

442
00:24:19,808 --> 00:24:22,691
I'm 100% used to actually working in the engine.

443
00:24:22,691 --> 00:24:25,112
These freezes, they're like, it's my Maya.

444
00:24:25,713 --> 00:24:28,814
You know, I don't need to leave the engine to do things.

445
00:24:28,814 --> 00:24:31,995
And the fact that I can actually do it so fast like this,

446
00:24:31,995 --> 00:24:33,555
it just makes my life that much easier.

447
00:24:33,555 --> 00:24:35,175
And it makes it more flexible for me too.

448
00:24:35,175 --> 00:24:39,357
I don't actually have to open another package to make a small change,

449
00:24:39,357 --> 00:24:40,577
resave, reload.

450
00:24:40,577 --> 00:24:40,937
No.

451
00:24:40,937 --> 00:24:42,558
I just grab a vertex, drag it up.

452
00:24:42,558 --> 00:24:43,158
Does it work?

