It's awesome.

479
00:26:27,113 --> 00:26:31,396
And it's cool that I was able to sort of inspire them in a certain direction, even though I'm

480
00:26:31,396 --> 00:26:32,317
not an artist myself.

481
00:26:32,317 --> 00:26:34,618
We have Lua scripting as well.

482
00:26:34,618 --> 00:26:40,522
So there's a way that we can actually add a little bit more functionality to our visual

483
00:26:40,522 --> 00:26:41,443
prototypes.

484
00:26:41,443 --> 00:26:43,844
It's not just all artsy-fartsy.

485
00:26:43,844 --> 00:26:45,165
But it's simple scripting.

486
00:26:45,165 --> 00:26:46,466
It's nothing too complicated.

487
00:26:46,466 --> 00:26:49,228
I picked this up very quickly, and I'm not really a programmer.

488
00:26:49,668 --> 00:26:55,412
So what we have is we have simple chunks of behavior, like a shake, a movement, ease in, ease out, things like that.

489
00:26:55,412 --> 00:26:58,974
And you can just sort of stick one in front of the other, it's a series of events.

490
00:26:58,974 --> 00:27:05,859
And that's how we can do simple things like moving an object down the screen, making a crusher that shakes and comes back.

491
00:27:05,859 --> 00:27:10,802
We can pretty much prototype everything we need to using these tweens, these movement tweens in Lua scripting,

492
00:27:10,802 --> 00:27:13,764
plus all the tools that I've shown you already in the editor.

493
00:27:15,070 --> 00:27:17,851
One thing we also like to do on this side of things

494
00:27:17,851 --> 00:27:21,072
is separate templates and instances.

495
00:27:21,072 --> 00:27:23,773
So basically, for all of our gameplay elements,

496
00:27:23,773 --> 00:27:26,774
we have templates which have a set series of behavior

497
00:27:26,774 --> 00:27:28,134
that is sort of like non-negotiable.

498
00:27:28,134 --> 00:27:28,934
It has to be that way.

499
00:27:28,934 --> 00:27:30,835
But there's always a couple of parameters

500
00:27:30,835 --> 00:27:31,835
that you can mess with a bit

501
00:27:31,835 --> 00:27:33,396
to do something different with it.

502
00:27:33,396 --> 00:27:35,056
And those are in the instance file.

503
00:27:35,056 --> 00:27:36,957
So that enables the designer

504
00:27:36,957 --> 00:27:38,497
to actually manipulate certain things

505
00:27:38,497 --> 00:27:40,938
in a way that fits his current situation

506
00:27:40,938 --> 00:27:42,478
without the game designer pulling his hair out

507
00:27:42,478 --> 00:27:44,719
that you're changing everything about the enemy, basically.

508
00:27:48,828 --> 00:27:50,112
We have a sequence editor too.

509
00:27:50,112 --> 00:27:54,263
This is sort of our cut scene tool in the UBR framework.

510
00:27:54,683 --> 00:27:59,886
Well, what's really interesting is sometimes when you go exploring in areas of an engine that you're not supposed to touch,

511
00:27:59,886 --> 00:28:02,327
you find out that it actually has something to bring to your job, too.

512
00:28:02,327 --> 00:28:06,750
And during Rayman Origins, I was in charge of building a boss

513
00:28:06,750 --> 00:28:08,551
inside of the stomach of a dragon.

514
00:28:08,551 --> 00:28:15,354
Lucky for me, there were no big animated characters that needed to be integrated with complex behavioral patterns and things like that.

515
00:28:15,354 --> 00:28:20,097
So I could use what I had at my disposal as a level designer to build an interesting boss sequence.

516
00:28:20,777 --> 00:28:25,620
So I took the sequence editor, I took things like these fire patches and other interesting gameplay elements,

517
00:28:25,620 --> 00:28:27,542
and I made a series of events.

518
00:28:27,542 --> 00:28:32,425
So, trigger flame, trigger flame, trigger the weak point, hit the weak point,

519
00:28:32,425 --> 00:28:35,407
if you don't, restart, if you do, go to the next sequence.

520
00:28:36,192 --> 00:28:41,355
And I was able to prototype 10, 20 different versions of this boss by myself, without a programmer,

521
00:28:41,355 --> 00:28:42,515
and in the end, it's a 100% level design boss.

522
00:28:42,515 --> 00:28:45,477
Which is something interesting. I wouldn't imagine I'd be able to do that,

523
00:28:45,477 --> 00:28:49,600
but this tool that wasn't meant for it was powerful enough and integrated well into the engine

524
00:28:49,600 --> 00:28:51,161
and the other systems that allowed me to do it.

525
00:28:51,161 --> 00:28:53,282
We also have a very interesting tool that I will not be able to explain to you.

526
00:29:01,521 --> 00:29:03,722
It's our animation tool in the engine.

527
00:29:03,722 --> 00:29:04,923
It's really, really cool.

528
00:29:04,923 --> 00:29:07,124
It allows us to hybridize hand-animated keyframes

529
00:29:07,124 --> 00:29:09,385
with bone animation.

530
00:29:09,385 --> 00:29:11,266
And actually, there was a talk last year

531
00:29:11,266 --> 00:29:14,007
by two of my colleagues where they explain everything

532
00:29:14,007 --> 00:29:15,688
there is to know about GenAnim.

533
00:29:15,688 --> 00:29:17,308
So since you all have access to the vault,

534
00:29:17,308 --> 00:29:19,389
I suggest you watch it when you get back to your studios.

535
00:29:19,389 --> 00:29:22,351
It's a very interesting talk, and it's definitely

536
00:29:22,351 --> 00:29:23,891
a cool tool worth checking out, especially

537
00:29:23,891 --> 00:29:25,472
if you're on the more artsy side of things.

538
00:29:27,283 --> 00:29:30,686
But I'm going to push through in the spirit of level design

539
00:29:30,686 --> 00:29:33,828
with some case studies in the production of Rayman Legends

540
00:29:33,828 --> 00:29:38,772
that greatly benefited from the workflow

541
00:29:38,772 --> 00:29:39,973
that I'm talking about, basically,

542
00:29:39,973 --> 00:29:41,795
because of the tools we have in the engine.

543
00:29:41,795 --> 00:29:44,897
So one of the things that I personally was tasked to do

544
00:29:44,897 --> 00:29:48,620
during the production was investigate stealth in Rayman.

545
00:29:48,620 --> 00:29:51,142
Rayman's a happy, flowy, platformy game.

546
00:29:51,142 --> 00:29:53,084
It's not usually something you want to slow down in.

547
00:29:53,084 --> 00:29:55,346
But we wanted you to feel a bit like a spy

548
00:29:55,346 --> 00:29:56,307
and avoid detection.

549
00:29:57,172 --> 00:29:58,892
but we had to preserve the flow.

550
00:29:58,892 --> 00:30:00,973
Because flow for us in Rayman is paramount.

551
00:30:00,973 --> 00:30:04,395
It's something that we need to have all the time.

552
00:30:04,395 --> 00:30:06,236
So how do you impose that on people?

553
00:30:06,236 --> 00:30:08,817
We played around with systems, we tested a lot,

554
00:30:08,817 --> 00:30:11,518
we threw a lot away, and we finally got to the thing

555
00:30:11,518 --> 00:30:12,379
that felt best.

556
00:30:12,379 --> 00:30:14,340
What I'm gonna show you now is a couple

557
00:30:14,340 --> 00:30:17,401
little prototype videos of the early shadow system

558
00:30:17,401 --> 00:30:19,582
and some interesting directions I took

559
00:30:19,582 --> 00:30:21,203
with developing new features.

560
00:30:24,630 --> 00:30:28,494
So, basically, when I was first working with these shadows,

561
00:30:28,494 --> 00:30:31,918
I realized that when there's something that's collidable, like ground,

562
00:30:31,918 --> 00:30:32,758
it would cast a shadow.

563
00:30:32,758 --> 00:30:35,281
And when there was no ground, it wouldn't cast a shadow.

564
00:30:35,281 --> 00:30:37,483
That meant that all of my situations

565
00:30:37,483 --> 00:30:39,926
had sort of like an empty void that you could fall into.

566
00:30:39,926 --> 00:30:42,748
And that doesn't really challenge the shadow or light mechanic.

567
00:30:42,748 --> 00:30:44,951
That just challenges avoiding falling through a pit.

568
00:30:45,511 --> 00:30:48,672
So how am I going to use that in an interesting way to reinforce the mechanic?

569
00:30:48,672 --> 00:30:51,173
And so I just took a template freeze,

570
00:30:51,173 --> 00:30:53,074
I made it semi-transparent in blue,

571
00:30:53,074 --> 00:30:55,935
and I didn't apply the shadow collision to it.

572
00:30:55,935 --> 00:30:56,255
And that's it.

573
00:30:56,255 --> 00:30:59,737
And all of a sudden now, I invented a new type of freeze

574
00:30:59,737 --> 00:31:00,957
that we had to add to the kit

575
00:31:00,957 --> 00:31:04,639
that was integral to making this shadow gameplay work in the final world.

576
00:31:05,399 --> 00:31:08,721
But before I could convince them, I had to convince them.

577
00:31:08,721 --> 00:31:12,864
So I had to make more prototypes that sort of stress tested

578
00:31:12,864 --> 00:31:17,587
or proved that it's really an interesting addition to the art kit

579
00:31:17,587 --> 00:31:19,968
and the tool set as a level designer.

580
00:31:19,968 --> 00:31:21,750
So I had to make a number of different prototypes

581
00:31:21,750 --> 00:31:24,491
that showed the use of the glass in different ways.

582
00:31:24,491 --> 00:31:25,672
And eventually it got approved.

583
00:31:26,298 --> 00:31:31,442
So then, there are many different uses in the final game.

584
00:31:31,442 --> 00:31:32,583
This is just one of them.

585
00:31:32,583 --> 00:31:38,567
It's an interesting combination of the basic sentry plus the glass.

586
00:31:38,567 --> 00:31:44,832
Another interesting example is these underwater snakes.

587
00:31:44,832 --> 00:31:47,714
They are not normally meant to be used this way.

588
00:31:47,714 --> 00:31:50,476
They didn't have the shadow functionality to begin with.

589
00:31:50,476 --> 00:31:51,537
They were meant for something else.

590
00:31:52,621 --> 00:31:55,222
But we thought, well if they're already there,

591
00:31:55,222 --> 00:31:58,284
why don't we just give them the shadow collision property,

592
00:31:58,284 --> 00:31:59,464
and that's it.

593
00:31:59,464 --> 00:32:00,825
So I just opened the script,

594
00:32:00,825 --> 00:32:02,866
I changed the material definition,

595
00:32:02,866 --> 00:32:04,427
and suddenly it was casting shadows,

596
00:32:04,427 --> 00:32:06,808
and it was a really interesting thing to use

597
00:32:06,808 --> 00:32:07,668
for the shadow gameplay.

598
00:32:07,668 --> 00:32:11,190
Easy peasy.

599
00:32:11,190 --> 00:32:12,771
And here it's just a simple matter of

600
00:32:12,771 --> 00:32:16,232
putting a trigger that pauses and unpauses the light.

601
00:32:16,232 --> 00:32:16,653
And that was it.

602
00:32:17,360 --> 00:32:21,964
And it worked. It really worked. It was very fast and it made it into the final game.

603
00:32:21,964 --> 00:32:29,330
One thing that was interesting for me though, is I made sure to make the flicker when I was doing this.

604
00:32:29,330 --> 00:32:32,493
Because you need to have clear signs and feedback to tell the player,

605
00:32:32,493 --> 00:32:35,595
okay, the light's going to turn on, the light's going to turn off.

606
00:32:35,595 --> 00:32:37,577
And it was important even in the prototype to prove that.

607
00:32:37,577 --> 00:32:42,741
So here, we actually had to work on a little thing called the Wii U for a while.

608
00:32:42,741 --> 00:32:44,903
And we had to make some prototypes for it.

609
00:32:45,847 --> 00:32:49,573
So, we had these elements you could pick up using the Wii U tablet.

610
00:32:49,573 --> 00:32:51,956
You could drag them around.

611
00:32:51,956 --> 00:32:54,581
And we had this shadow casting thing.

612
00:32:54,581 --> 00:32:57,966
So I thought, why not parent one to the other and see what happens.

613
00:32:57,966 --> 00:32:58,367
And this happened.

614
00:32:58,367 --> 00:32:59,649
And it worked.

615
00:33:00,333 --> 00:33:04,035
So we ended up making a different version of the light casting thing.

616
00:33:04,035 --> 00:33:07,097
We integrated the components of being able to carry it on the screen.

617
00:33:07,097 --> 00:33:09,939
And we had a new gameplay element to use in different situations.

618
00:33:09,939 --> 00:33:11,841
And it was sort of just like a happy experiment.

619
00:33:11,841 --> 00:33:13,121
A happy accident, actually.

620
00:33:13,121 --> 00:33:16,164
I just, I thought, why can't I combine these two things?

621
00:33:16,164 --> 00:33:17,885
So I tried, and they worked.

622
00:33:17,885 --> 00:33:22,428
And that's really the biggest thing in this engine for me, I think.

623
00:33:22,428 --> 00:33:26,330
Is it's just like, taking two things that don't really belong together,

624
00:33:26,330 --> 00:33:28,132
and sort of thinking like, well why not?

625
00:33:28,132 --> 00:33:29,893
They could, right?

626
00:33:30,901 --> 00:33:32,842
And this is another example of that.

627
00:33:32,842 --> 00:33:35,344
We have this thing in the game, digging,

628
00:33:35,344 --> 00:33:36,886
where basically on the touch screen,

629
00:33:36,886 --> 00:33:40,929
you can touch these cakes and dig tunnels for your friends.

630
00:33:40,929 --> 00:33:43,771
We wanted to reuse this mechanic for the rest of the world

631
00:33:43,771 --> 00:33:45,172
to make it consistent.

632
00:33:45,172 --> 00:33:47,874
But not every level needed to have the touch screen gameplay.

633
00:33:47,874 --> 00:33:49,815
We didn't want to force that on the player for every level.

634
00:33:49,815 --> 00:33:53,939
So what we tried to do was separate the functionality

635
00:33:53,939 --> 00:33:57,341
and combine it with other things to give the same feeling,

636
00:33:57,341 --> 00:33:58,402
but in a different way.

637
00:34:00,965 --> 00:34:03,169
So I used the parenting system, of course, that we have.

638
00:34:03,169 --> 00:34:05,633
We had a separate actor for the digging,

639
00:34:05,633 --> 00:34:08,238
and allowed us to have flexibility in prototyping,

640
00:34:08,238 --> 00:34:09,360
because we just said.

641
00:34:10,013 --> 00:34:12,415
I think that this thing should be able to dig through cakes.

642
00:34:12,415 --> 00:34:14,958
So you parent the object to it and you see what happens.

643
00:34:14,958 --> 00:34:15,859
Okay, that doesn't work.

644
00:34:15,859 --> 00:34:18,262
You try something else, you move on.

645
00:34:18,262 --> 00:34:19,803
If something starts to work, okay, cool.

646
00:34:19,803 --> 00:34:22,066
You move on from there and do a number of different prototypes.

647
00:34:22,066 --> 00:34:25,249
And eventually, you integrate the component

648
00:34:25,249 --> 00:34:26,690
into the gameplay element.

649
00:34:26,690 --> 00:34:29,894
So, every snake now has this digging component,

650
00:34:29,894 --> 00:34:32,236
and when you put it in these sort of digging cakes,

651
00:34:32,236 --> 00:34:33,137
they start to dig tunnels.

652
00:34:37,246 --> 00:34:40,269
So here, for example, you've got this lovely dancing skeleton.

653
00:34:40,269 --> 00:34:44,154
And this is how the digging works, basically,

654
00:34:44,154 --> 00:34:44,895
with the touchscreen.

655
00:34:44,895 --> 00:34:47,598
But what I'm going to grab over here

656
00:34:47,598 --> 00:34:48,979
is the actor that's separate.

657
00:34:48,979 --> 00:34:52,563
And you can see it has the exact same functionality,

658
00:34:52,563 --> 00:34:55,707
but it's not attached to the touchscreen gameplay.

659
00:34:56,571 --> 00:34:58,752
So what I'm going to do is use our parenting system

660
00:34:58,752 --> 00:35:02,873
and you can actually see all the bones in the character

661
00:35:02,873 --> 00:35:05,435
and you can parent anything to any of the bones.

662
00:35:05,435 --> 00:35:07,075
So I could parent something to the hand of the guy

663
00:35:07,075 --> 00:35:08,796
and it'll be attached to his hand

664
00:35:08,796 --> 00:35:11,757
and when he moves it up and down, it'll move with him.

665
00:35:11,757 --> 00:35:13,678
It's really, really strangely powerful.

666
00:35:13,678 --> 00:35:16,479
And now you can see that as he walks around,

667
00:35:16,479 --> 00:35:17,779
he's destroying the cake.

668
00:35:17,779 --> 00:35:19,660
And that's what I did with the snakes.

669
00:35:19,660 --> 00:35:22,121
The snakes were more interesting than this guy,

670
00:35:22,121 --> 00:35:22,902
so I stuck with the snakes.

671
00:35:25,677 --> 00:35:28,607
But there are some other interesting cases too.

672
00:35:28,607 --> 00:35:31,616
For example, there's this really big luchador.

673
00:35:33,777 --> 00:35:37,719
And one thing that's interesting about this case is

674
00:35:37,719 --> 00:35:39,320
the original version of this

675
00:35:39,320 --> 00:35:41,641
there was this flat ground, he jumped, he landed

676
00:35:41,641 --> 00:35:43,322
and he sat there and you had to kill him.

677
00:35:43,322 --> 00:35:45,723
But because of his animation and the way that he was

678
00:35:45,723 --> 00:35:47,244
it just felt a bit weird.

679
00:35:47,244 --> 00:35:49,285
So what they did was the level designer just

680
00:35:49,285 --> 00:35:50,525
dropped some digging at the bottom

681
00:35:50,525 --> 00:35:52,847
and put the digging component into the guy.

682
00:35:52,847 --> 00:35:55,028
All of a sudden he jumps off,

683
00:35:55,028 --> 00:35:57,409
falls into the abyss, it solves one problem

684
00:35:57,409 --> 00:35:59,210
and it creates an extra danger behind the player

685
00:35:59,210 --> 00:36:00,350
which pushes him forward.

686
00:36:00,920 --> 00:36:01,580
Problem solved.

687
00:36:01,580 --> 00:36:05,982
And it's just a matter of replacing one little functionality for another

688
00:36:05,982 --> 00:36:08,783
and seeing what happens.

689
00:36:08,783 --> 00:36:10,223
And here's the snakes I was talking about.

690
00:36:10,223 --> 00:36:14,725
It's really interesting because you can make all kinds of interesting tunnels,

691
00:36:14,725 --> 00:36:17,706
configurations, with different snakes digging through.

692
00:36:17,706 --> 00:36:20,547
And visually it's really interesting too. It's very different from something that

693
00:36:20,547 --> 00:36:22,488
you would normally get with a player controlling it.

694
00:36:22,488 --> 00:36:24,729
Usually they'll just wipe the screen clean and done.

695
00:36:24,729 --> 00:36:28,010
But here you've actually got a nice, tailored level design

696
00:36:28,010 --> 00:36:30,591
that's created and generated by these enemies in the game.

697
00:36:33,674 --> 00:36:35,976
This is an example that I'm particularly proud of,

698
00:36:35,976 --> 00:36:36,996
because I did it.

699
00:36:36,996 --> 00:36:42,860
It was basically just, we were between projects,

700
00:36:42,860 --> 00:36:44,601
after Rayman Origins was finished,

701
00:36:44,601 --> 00:36:46,643
and we were playing around with some adversarial gameplay.

702
00:36:46,643 --> 00:36:49,324
You know, it's a co-op game, but we like to smack each other.

703
00:36:49,324 --> 00:36:51,786
Can we make that a thing?

704
00:36:51,786 --> 00:36:54,008
We wanted slight randomness, because otherwise one guy

705
00:36:54,008 --> 00:36:56,109
dominates and everybody feels bad, and we don't want that.

706
00:36:56,109 --> 00:36:56,869
We're a family game.

707
00:36:56,869 --> 00:36:58,150
Everyone should feel good.

708
00:36:59,975 --> 00:37:02,237
And it needed to be a convincing prototype.

709
00:37:02,237 --> 00:37:03,578
Because if it's not a convincing prototype,

710
00:37:03,578 --> 00:37:07,321
you're not convincing anyone, are you?

711
00:37:07,321 --> 00:37:08,662
So, ultimately, this is what it is.

712
00:37:08,662 --> 00:37:10,903
It's just a soccer ball, and you can kick it around.

713
00:37:10,903 --> 00:37:12,745
It's fun in four players.

714
00:37:12,745 --> 00:37:13,826
People can smack each other.

715
00:37:13,826 --> 00:37:16,007
It's two versus two, three versus one,

716
00:37:16,007 --> 00:37:16,928
all that kind of good stuff.

717
00:37:16,928 --> 00:37:19,770
And what it basically started was,

718
00:37:19,770 --> 00:37:22,693
was I just tossed a projectile from an enemy in Rayman

719
00:37:22,693 --> 00:37:23,093
Origins.

720
00:37:23,093 --> 00:37:26,656
He threw boulders, and they bounced once or twice.

721
00:37:26,656 --> 00:37:27,777
The ironic thing is that.

722
00:37:29,017 --> 00:37:31,277
after they bounced once or twice, they died.

723
00:37:31,277 --> 00:37:32,438
It exploded.

724
00:37:32,438 --> 00:37:34,499
So I had one shot to get it into a goal,

725
00:37:34,499 --> 00:37:36,659
and otherwise I had to restart the map.

726
00:37:36,659 --> 00:37:38,660
So it wasn't really easy to prototype that one,

727
00:37:38,660 --> 00:37:39,901
but it proved a point.

728
00:37:39,901 --> 00:37:42,982
It felt good to try to kick a ball into a goal.

729
00:37:42,982 --> 00:37:46,143
So then I made a trigger that detected the ball exclusively,

730
00:37:46,143 --> 00:37:47,823
and when I triggered something,

731
00:37:47,823 --> 00:37:48,864
for example, I had numbers.

732
00:37:49,544 --> 00:37:52,707
And I would just say, when the ball enters, shift the numbers up.

733
00:37:52,707 --> 00:37:53,909
So it says 1, now it's 2, now it's 3.

734
00:37:53,909 --> 00:37:58,133
It was like a really rudimentary, messy prototype.

735
00:37:58,133 --> 00:38:00,276
But on the outside when you're playing it, you don't feel it.

736
00:38:00,276 --> 00:38:02,478
You don't know that it's a messy prototype.

737
00:38:02,478 --> 00:38:04,340
It feels like what it's supposed to be.

738
00:38:04,340 --> 00:38:05,822
So then we developed it.

739
00:38:05,822 --> 00:38:06,863
That was the final version.

740
00:38:06,863 --> 00:38:08,184
This is the first version.

741
00:38:08,765 --> 00:38:16,068
This is actually something internal. We did this for our Rayman Origins release party, actually.

742
00:38:16,068 --> 00:38:21,070
In the final version, you've got some nice little enemies dancing in the foreground when you kick the ball in.

743
00:38:21,070 --> 00:38:24,271
For this version, we have our lovely creative director's face on it.

744
00:38:26,132 --> 00:38:30,295
but it was good fun. And actually, what's interesting to note here, we had moving goals,

745
00:38:30,295 --> 00:38:34,737
multiball at the top, bouncing surfaces for the floor, and we removed all of them for

746
00:38:34,737 --> 00:38:39,140
the final version. It was fun, we could have done more, but we felt that the simple version

747
00:38:39,140 --> 00:38:42,922
was clear enough and we had more things to focus on. But it was a lot of fun. And the

748
00:38:42,922 --> 00:38:47,364
reason that we kept it was because we made the prototype, we brought it to our Rayman

749
00:38:47,364 --> 00:38:48,505
Origins release party.

750
00:38:49,045 --> 00:38:50,627
and everybody started playing it.

751
00:38:50,627 --> 00:38:53,409
And they couldn't stop for the entire evening.

752
00:38:53,409 --> 00:38:56,512
Can you imagine, in the evening you're supposed to be drinking

753
00:38:56,512 --> 00:39:00,435
and celebrating that you're done with that freaking game?

754
00:39:00,435 --> 00:39:02,677
You don't have to look at it anymore.

755
00:39:02,677 --> 00:39:03,918
Yeah, party hardy.

756
00:39:03,918 --> 00:39:06,100
And everyone wants to play the prototype?

757
00:39:06,100 --> 00:39:07,321
It just doesn't make any sense.

758
00:39:07,321 --> 00:39:08,362
But it told us something.

759
00:39:08,362 --> 00:39:10,103
It knew that it was actually quite special.

760
00:39:10,103 --> 00:39:10,624
So we pushed it forward,

761
00:39:10,624 --> 00:39:12,465
and it made it into the final game.

762
00:39:12,465 --> 00:39:14,687
So, through all of this,

763
00:39:14,687 --> 00:39:15,408
I mean, what went right?

764
00:39:16,804 --> 00:39:18,065
Obviously a lot went right, right?

765
00:39:18,065 --> 00:39:20,767
Otherwise I wouldn't be here talking about it like this.

766
00:39:20,767 --> 00:39:21,728
Or I'm just hopelessly optimistic.

767
00:39:21,728 --> 00:39:25,831
Well, there's the rapid iterative failure thing.

768
00:39:25,831 --> 00:39:27,012
We did fail a lot.

769
00:39:27,012 --> 00:39:29,494
We failed hard sometimes, less hard other times.

770
00:39:29,494 --> 00:39:32,656
But we failed consistently, and that was by design.

771
00:39:32,656 --> 00:39:35,718
We knew that the better off we were,

772
00:39:35,718 --> 00:39:38,520
we were better off by building a lot of things,

773
00:39:38,520 --> 00:39:40,602
throwing them away, building more, throwing them away,

774
00:39:40,602 --> 00:39:42,443
and then putting all of our eggs into one basket

775
00:39:42,443 --> 00:39:44,805
and realizing when it was too late that it wasn't working.

776
00:39:47,074 --> 00:39:51,119
our actors, our templates, the freeze system, which I'm sure impressed a number of you.

777
00:39:51,119 --> 00:39:56,546
All of these different systems, they're obviously going right, because they allow us to do our

778
00:39:56,546 --> 00:39:59,690
job so fast, it's unimaginable, until you try it.

779
00:39:59,690 --> 00:40:05,017
And we're a small team, for ease of communication.

780
00:40:06,029 --> 00:40:08,890
Because with a tool like this as well, you don't need so many people.

781
00:40:08,890 --> 00:40:09,851
You know, you build systems.

782
00:40:09,851 --> 00:40:12,652
It's like, it's procedural, which is what everyone's doing these days.

783
00:40:12,652 --> 00:40:13,573
It's kind of a hot topic.

784
00:40:13,573 --> 00:40:16,134
It is relatively procedural, the way that it's set up.

785
00:40:16,134 --> 00:40:17,675
These freezes and everything.

786
00:40:17,675 --> 00:40:19,276
It saves a lot of people a lot of time.

787
00:40:20,217 --> 00:40:23,718
And also having a small team is great, because you can actually go up to somebody who's right

788
00:40:23,718 --> 00:40:27,240
next to your programmer and smack him for something or tell him this or that.

789
00:40:27,240 --> 00:40:31,623
There's not this sort of like hierarchy or you have to report to his lead and this and

790
00:40:31,623 --> 00:40:32,123
that.

791
00:40:32,123 --> 00:40:36,785
We're a small team, we work together in little strike teams sometimes, other times we're

792
00:40:36,785 --> 00:40:41,128
in our big level design group, programming group, but we're all in the same little villa

793
00:40:41,128 --> 00:40:41,648
in France.

794
00:40:41,648 --> 00:40:44,930
It doesn't really make a difference when I have to go upstairs to the water cooler and

795
00:40:44,930 --> 00:40:46,771
talk to somebody or just down the hall.

796
00:40:48,918 --> 00:40:53,019
And of course there's the simplicity of workflow and the flexible systems,

797
00:40:53,019 --> 00:40:55,700
which I've hopefully demonstrated to you guys already,

798
00:40:55,700 --> 00:40:57,621
but they're there and they work very, very well.

799
00:40:57,621 --> 00:41:01,642
Of course, everyone makes mistakes.

800
00:41:01,642 --> 00:41:04,543
When you say that failure is sort of by design in your workflow,

801
00:41:04,543 --> 00:41:05,663
you're going to fail a lot, but

802
00:41:05,663 --> 00:41:08,104
we didn't really do design documentation.

803
00:41:08,104 --> 00:41:11,645
You can imagine that when you're working extremely quickly,

804
00:41:11,645 --> 00:41:13,266
when do you find the time to write things down?

805
00:41:13,266 --> 00:41:16,527
And when you do write things down, aren't they obsolete?

806
00:41:17,022 --> 00:41:19,884
that's pretty much the way that it went for us.

807
00:41:19,884 --> 00:41:21,325
But the bad part about this

808
00:41:21,325 --> 00:41:23,187
is the fact that when someone new joins a team,

809
00:41:23,187 --> 00:41:24,908
they don't really have a resource to go to.

810
00:41:24,908 --> 00:41:27,129
They can't just say, like, oh, read the Bible.

811
00:41:27,129 --> 00:41:28,891
And then there you go, you go through it,

812
00:41:28,891 --> 00:41:31,292
and you figure out everything, and then you start working.

813
00:41:31,292 --> 00:41:32,773
We have a help menu in the editor, which is good.

814
00:41:32,773 --> 00:41:34,034
It's a good base.

815
00:41:34,034 --> 00:41:35,755
But for example, the design of the game.

816
00:41:35,755 --> 00:41:37,617
No, no, we're not ready yet.

817
00:41:37,617 --> 00:41:38,998
We're still experimenting.

818
00:41:38,998 --> 00:41:39,978
We have two months left.

819
00:41:39,978 --> 00:41:41,119
Well, we're still experimenting.

820
00:41:41,119 --> 00:41:41,540
We'll see.

821
00:41:44,980 --> 00:41:47,242
Sometimes we had a lack of tools for specific tasks.

822
00:41:47,242 --> 00:41:49,444
I mean, we have some great systems in there,

823
00:41:49,444 --> 00:41:53,268
but there are some other processes that are a little bit more tedious,

824
00:41:53,268 --> 00:41:55,430
less flexible, basically.

825
00:41:55,430 --> 00:41:57,953
And sometimes we could have communicated better on what we needed,

826
00:41:57,953 --> 00:42:02,077
so that way we could actually work more efficiently.

827
00:42:02,077 --> 00:42:05,600
And there was a lack of communication of engine workflow issues.

828
00:42:06,327 --> 00:42:08,809
Because the thing is, when you're used to working so fast,

829
00:42:08,809 --> 00:42:10,830
and trying to pump things out very quickly,

830
00:42:10,830 --> 00:42:14,473
when you realize that you have to do a very tedious workaround for something,

831
00:42:14,473 --> 00:42:16,255
just to get it to work,

832
00:42:16,255 --> 00:42:18,096
you take the extra 10 seconds to do the workaround,

833
00:42:18,096 --> 00:42:19,758
rather than telling somebody,

834
00:42:19,758 --> 00:42:23,741
the parenting system isn't working, you have to parent three times instead of one.

835
00:42:23,741 --> 00:42:25,442
But it's like, oh, whatever, I'm sure they know,

836
00:42:25,442 --> 00:42:28,545
and I work with it, and then like six months later,

837
00:42:28,545 --> 00:42:29,526
I hope someone knows.

838
00:42:30,445 --> 00:42:32,587
but you keep working with it instead of just going.

839
00:42:32,587 --> 00:42:34,630
And if I just went to the guy and told him it's not working,

840
00:42:34,630 --> 00:42:35,951
it would be fixed in the next build.

841
00:42:35,951 --> 00:42:38,213
But it's just this mentality that we get into of, just deal with it.

842
00:42:38,213 --> 00:42:38,974
Just push forward.

843
00:42:38,974 --> 00:42:41,677
You're going to fail anyway, so you might as well just keep going.

844
00:42:41,677 --> 00:42:44,960
And when you hit something that's good, then you improve it.

845
00:42:44,960 --> 00:42:46,321
But the engine is a different story.

846
00:42:46,321 --> 00:42:48,283
And sometimes we have to realize that.

847
00:42:50,384 --> 00:42:53,206
And there, of course, was sometimes a lack of communication

848
00:42:53,206 --> 00:42:54,787
of new features and additions.

849
00:42:54,787 --> 00:42:56,788
Because we worked so informally sometimes,

850
00:42:56,788 --> 00:42:59,550
going straight to a programmer and asking for a new feature,

851
00:42:59,550 --> 00:43:01,631
that meant that there were times that a new feature was created,

852
00:43:01,631 --> 00:43:05,354
and one level designer knew about it,

853
00:43:05,354 --> 00:43:06,255
and he didn't tell the rest of us.

854
00:43:06,255 --> 00:43:07,075
And we lost a lot of time.

855
00:43:07,075 --> 00:43:09,957
And then some guy comes up to me a year and a half later,

856
00:43:09,957 --> 00:43:15,941
and says that we had the thing all that time,

857
00:43:15,941 --> 00:43:18,803
and I've been doing it the wrong way.

858
00:43:19,912 --> 00:43:20,513
People get annoyed.

859
00:43:20,513 --> 00:43:23,215
And it's definitely something we need to work on.

860
00:43:23,215 --> 00:43:25,196
But it's cool when you get new features.

861
00:43:25,196 --> 00:43:28,679
Just tell people when they come out at the beginning.

862
00:43:28,679 --> 00:43:33,983
So it's not just Rayman in the UBR framework.

863
00:43:33,983 --> 00:43:36,505
It started with Rayman, but it's sort of evolved since then.

864
00:43:36,505 --> 00:43:39,908
We actually do mobile games in UBR as well.

865
00:43:39,908 --> 00:43:41,570
Rayman Fiesta Run, Rayman Jungle Run.

866
00:43:41,570 --> 00:43:43,151
Actually, can I have a show of hands

867
00:43:43,151 --> 00:43:45,293
who's played one of the new Rayman games, from Origins

868
00:43:45,293 --> 00:43:46,213
to Legends to Mobile?

869
00:43:48,316 --> 00:43:49,661
Not bad.

870
00:43:49,661 --> 00:43:52,831
Good job, guys.

871
00:43:52,831 --> 00:43:54,898
Thanks for helping me survive and eat every day.

872
00:43:56,517 --> 00:44:02,783
So we do mobile, but we're also exper- well, not me personally, but Ubisoft is experimenting

873
00:44:02,783 --> 00:44:04,945
with other genres in UbiArt, of course.

874
00:44:04,945 --> 00:44:09,308
So in Montreal, they're working on a Japanese RPG, Child of Light, using the same framework.

875
00:44:09,308 --> 00:44:13,732
It's still a 2D game, it's still using a lot of the similar systems, but they're adding

876
00:44:13,732 --> 00:44:18,296
some really cool features that we didn't necessarily add for our projects, but it's cool for us

877
00:44:18,296 --> 00:44:21,759
to see how other teams adapt and impact the development of the engine.

878
00:44:24,395 --> 00:44:26,938
And of course, we also have another one, Valiant Hearts,

879
00:44:26,938 --> 00:44:29,001
which is a World War I adventure game

880
00:44:29,001 --> 00:44:31,405
that's being developed actually by the guys

881
00:44:31,405 --> 00:44:32,206
who did Rayman Legends.

882
00:44:33,173 --> 00:44:37,334
I'm not on the team personally, I have other things to do, but a lot of my friends are

883
00:44:37,334 --> 00:44:37,914
working on it.

884
00:44:37,914 --> 00:44:40,555
You should buy it, it's going to be great.

885
00:44:40,555 --> 00:44:45,137
And it's a really cool game, it's different to have something that's a bit slower paced,

886
00:44:45,137 --> 00:44:49,158
less action-y, more emotional and everything, and having an adventure game in an engine

887
00:44:49,158 --> 00:44:50,839
that was built originally for a platformer.

888
00:44:50,839 --> 00:44:55,780
But it's working, it's an interesting take on the genre, and we're trying to push forward

889
00:44:55,780 --> 00:44:57,741
and see what we can do with the engine from there.

890
00:45:00,723 --> 00:45:03,484
I actually write sometimes for the Ubisoft Ubi blog.

891
00:45:03,484 --> 00:45:06,805
I've written a couple columns about working in the engine,

892
00:45:06,805 --> 00:45:10,966
working on the games, and working with the artists,

893
00:45:10,966 --> 00:45:14,987
and trying not to fight with them, and all that kind of stuff.

894
00:45:14,987 --> 00:45:16,847
And they could be quite interesting for you to check in,

895
00:45:16,847 --> 00:45:18,668
especially if you found this presentation interesting,

896
00:45:18,668 --> 00:45:20,048
despite the blackout.

897
00:45:20,048 --> 00:45:21,969
You might want to check this out and have some further reading.

898
00:45:21,969 --> 00:45:26,190
Just to give me some hits anyway, you know?

899
00:45:26,190 --> 00:45:26,250
So...

900
00:45:27,970 --> 00:45:30,131
If I'm going to give you a couple things to take away,

901
00:45:30,131 --> 00:45:33,512
apart from the fact that have a good engine that empowers your artists and designers,

902
00:45:33,512 --> 00:45:35,112
which is a given,

903
00:45:35,112 --> 00:45:36,312
fail often.

904
00:45:36,312 --> 00:45:37,672
Don't be scared of it.

905
00:45:37,672 --> 00:45:39,833
You know, plan for it.

906
00:45:39,833 --> 00:45:40,593
Or don't plan.

907
00:45:40,593 --> 00:45:41,653
Why do we need to plan failure?

908
00:45:41,653 --> 00:45:44,274
Let's just build stuff and see what happens.

909
00:45:44,274 --> 00:45:47,655
Try to make the most efficient, fast process that you can

910
00:45:47,655 --> 00:45:49,595
for getting to that sort of proof of concept stage.

911
00:45:49,595 --> 00:45:52,916
Get there, see if it's working, or move on.

912
00:45:52,916 --> 00:45:54,236
But that's it.

913
00:45:54,236 --> 00:45:57,037
Just push to fail often and you'll eventually stumble on the right thing.

914
00:45:59,047 --> 00:46:00,368
embrace artistic constraints.

915
00:46:00,368 --> 00:46:01,829
A lot of people think,

916
00:46:01,829 --> 00:46:04,812
oh, constraints, oh, they're so constraining.

917
00:46:04,812 --> 00:46:08,456
But they're not.

918
00:46:08,456 --> 00:46:10,398
They really push you to be more creative

919
00:46:10,398 --> 00:46:11,839
and work outside of your comfort zone.

920
00:46:11,839 --> 00:46:14,302
There have been so many times

921
00:46:14,302 --> 00:46:15,202
that I'm given a new art kit

922
00:46:15,202 --> 00:46:16,344
in a new world and I'm like,

923
00:46:16,344 --> 00:46:17,425
what am I supposed to do with this?

924
00:46:17,425 --> 00:46:18,526
Come on, guys.

925
00:46:18,526 --> 00:46:18,866
And then I think,

926
00:46:18,866 --> 00:46:20,828
oh no, but actually I can do something

927
00:46:20,828 --> 00:46:21,909
I've never done before.

928
00:46:21,909 --> 00:46:23,471
And that's the point.

929
00:46:24,113 --> 00:46:27,095
If they just gave us the same kit, re-skinned every time,

930
00:46:27,095 --> 00:46:30,256
we'd be making the same levels every time, we wouldn't move anywhere.

931
00:46:30,256 --> 00:46:32,377
And now we have worlds that are very unique,

932
00:46:32,377 --> 00:46:34,217
different gameplay elements, different direction.

933
00:46:34,217 --> 00:46:38,259
And it's because of these artistic constraints that we sort of have to live with

934
00:46:38,259 --> 00:46:39,259
and embrace.

935
00:46:39,259 --> 00:46:42,300
And my personal motto is,

936
00:46:42,300 --> 00:46:45,261
waste your own time, not someone else's.

937
00:46:45,261 --> 00:46:48,903
I'm very happy to spend a lot of time making my prototypes,

938
00:46:48,903 --> 00:46:50,583
trying to prove people that it's going to work.

939
00:46:51,907 --> 00:46:56,130
And I don't mind if I have to throw it away, because I know I'm not impacting the rest of the production.

940
00:46:56,130 --> 00:47:00,114
I can make up for my own lost time, but I don't want to feel guilty for somebody else's.

941
00:47:00,114 --> 00:47:05,138
And so you have to find a way to really clearly express yourself and your ideas so that everybody understands

942
00:47:05,138 --> 00:47:08,181
and knows where you want to go with it, and we can make it together.

943
00:47:08,181 --> 00:47:14,386
So that's it. Check us out at the UB Lounge upstairs. We're doing demos of the engine.

944
00:47:14,386 --> 00:47:16,488
And I hope you appreciated it, and thanks for being here.

945
00:47:28,278 --> 00:47:31,580
As far as I know, I think there's some time for questions if anyone has it.

946
00:47:31,580 --> 00:47:36,521
You have to step up to the mic, and otherwise I'll be in the wrap-up room after the question time.

947
00:47:36,521 --> 00:47:43,964
Can you talk about the process for choosing the concepts and art kits for the levels, and who's involved in those discussions?

948
00:47:44,853 --> 00:47:56,281
Yeah, so the people that choose the art kits that we use, basically the artists do the concepts, of course, and there's always a higher level artist or creative person that oversees it and stuff like that.

949
00:47:56,281 --> 00:48:09,230
And they just sort of decide, okay, this one's interesting, not clean enough. They have to be able to visualize the gameplay as well. If they can't really see how this concept is going to translate to the level or be clear enough, then they go back to the drawing board and...

950
00:48:09,530 --> 00:48:13,073
you know, revamp it a little bit or throw it away and try something new.

951
00:48:13,073 --> 00:48:15,996
There are worlds we didn't include in the game because

952
00:48:15,996 --> 00:48:18,938
they didn't work as well as others and we didn't have the time to make them work.

953
00:48:18,938 --> 00:48:21,920
But so basically it just comes down to people working hard

954
00:48:21,920 --> 00:48:25,763
and somebody above them telling them it's good enough or it's not.

955
00:48:25,763 --> 00:48:26,744
Business as usual, you know.

956
00:48:26,744 --> 00:48:26,824
Sure.

957
00:48:26,824 --> 00:48:26,924
Hey.

958
00:48:26,924 --> 00:48:31,128
So you talked a lot about the art impacting the design

959
00:48:31,128 --> 00:48:37,693
and I was wondering if there are any instances where the art impacted things on the programming side.

960
00:48:39,177 --> 00:48:40,268
Uh, yeah, I mean...

961
00:48:41,999 --> 00:48:45,400
I'm guessing there's a lot of times when, especially in a game like this that's cartoony,

962
00:48:45,400 --> 00:48:50,601
that the animations sort of guide the way that you program certain functionality, right?

963
00:48:50,601 --> 00:48:55,222
