00:52:46,149 --> 00:52:49,951
who uses UbiArt at the moment and he can actually open everything and show you

1056
00:52:49,951 --> 00:52:51,192
all those tools and how it works

1057
00:52:51,192 --> 00:52:55,175
so you can get some real details. Because I'm just a level designer. But it's more or less like that.

1058
00:52:55,175 --> 00:53:00,158
You I think? Yeah I had a question about Rayman Legends, about the musical levels.

1059
00:53:00,158 --> 00:53:06,382
So you mentioned working with the artists to create a look and feel.

1060
00:53:06,382 --> 00:53:10,605
Can you tell me, was there a different process making musical levels considering

1061
00:53:10,605 --> 00:53:12,146
their very sync to the beats?

1062
00:53:13,584 --> 00:53:20,807
That's an interesting one. Actually it was just sort of like a happy accident that we started making musical levels.

1063
00:53:20,807 --> 00:53:29,072
We were just making some challenges and we made a video of it to show internally and put some really cool rock music synchronized with the action in the video.

1064
00:53:29,072 --> 00:53:30,693
And after they showed that it was kind of like...

1065
00:53:31,077 --> 00:53:32,718
Can we play with the music?

1066
00:53:32,718 --> 00:53:34,358
I mean, is this real or is this just a video?

1067
00:53:34,358 --> 00:53:36,639
And it's like, well, no, but maybe we can make it.

1068
00:53:36,639 --> 00:53:38,060
And so then they started building a system

1069
00:53:38,060 --> 00:53:40,461
for synchronizing the gameplay to the music.

1070
00:53:40,461 --> 00:53:42,602
The composer, Christophe Héral,

1071
00:53:42,602 --> 00:53:44,042
he made the original version of the song,

1072
00:53:44,042 --> 00:53:46,743
and then the level designer built a level based on it,

1073
00:53:46,743 --> 00:53:48,264
and then it was a process of back and forth

1074
00:53:48,264 --> 00:53:50,485
between the two of them to make the final product.

1075
00:53:50,485 --> 00:53:52,005
And then, of course, the animators came in

1076
00:53:52,005 --> 00:53:53,346
and did all the fun animations,

1077
00:53:53,346 --> 00:53:54,767
background art, things like that.

1078
00:53:54,767 --> 00:53:54,847
You.

1079
00:53:58,369 --> 00:54:02,395
How much do you think the editor evolved during this frame?

1080
00:54:02,395 --> 00:54:09,065
I mean, it sounds like you create the levels, the graphics guy creates the graphics, but the editor just was there somehow.

1081
00:54:09,065 --> 00:54:13,752
How many new features came up, or had to be done by the programmers?

1082
00:54:14,160 --> 00:54:20,442
Lots changed. I mean, if you look at the, for example, just the touchscreen functionality alone, or the three-dimensional

1083
00:54:20,442 --> 00:54:27,305
entities in the game, they just weren't there. And those are a big chunk of what makes Rayman Legends different from Rayman Origins, right?

1084
00:54:27,305 --> 00:54:35,169
We also had a lighting system that wasn't there at all. It changes everything about the way the artists decorate their levels.

1085
00:54:35,169 --> 00:54:39,250
If you actually press a button to turn off the lights, the levels look really bad.

1086
00:54:40,363 --> 00:54:43,746
like in more Rayman Origins we worked with it and we made the levels look like they were

1087
00:54:43,746 --> 00:54:48,770
maybe lit, but it was a different style. But here, you turn it off, and so it's important

1088
00:54:48,770 --> 00:54:52,874
that it was developed properly. And so there are big, big features like that that really

1089
00:54:52,874 --> 00:54:57,098
impacted the way that we started to produce things. And there were just so many countless

1090
00:54:57,098 --> 00:55:02,162
little features, I can't even remember, because I'm just used to the current version. But

1091
00:55:02,162 --> 00:55:07,367
it was a very different tool when we did Rayman Origins, and it's improved a lot since.

